<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="238">
A proposito de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">Acropyga pickeli Borgm</taxonomicName>
. (1927) (Hym. 
<taxonomicName family="Formicidae" pageNumber="238" rank="family">Formicidae</taxonomicName>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="238">
Em setembro do anno passado enviei alguns cotypos dessa formiga (vide Rev. de Ent. vol. 1, p. 105) ao conheeido myrmecologo Prof. William Morton Wheeler (Harvard University, Museum of Comparative Zoology, Cambridge, Mass.), pedindo-lhe o obsequio de examinal-os e dizerme a sua opiniao sobre a questao ultimamente levantada por Costa Lima (Boletim Biologico, Rio, fasc. 17, agosto1931, pp. 2-9) da pretendida identidade de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">Acropyga pickeli Borgm</taxonomicName>
. com 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24951" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga goeldii Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goeldii">A. goeldii For</taxonomicName>
. e 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24941" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga decedens (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decedens">A. decedens Mayr</taxonomicName>
. Em carta datada de 2 de fevereiro deste anno, o Prof. Wheeler me respondcu o seguinte:
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="238">
«Dear Father Borgmeier: On returning from Australia I find your letter of September 9th and the specimens of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">Acropyga pickeli</taxonomicName>
awaiting me. I have compared the workers of the species with a cotype of Forel's 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24951" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga goeldii Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goeldii">goeldii</taxonomicName>
which he gave me many years ago. 1 think tthere is not the slightest doubt
</paragraph>
<paragraph>
<pageBorder>-------------------------------- page break --------------------------------</pageBorder>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">
<pageTitle>Rev. de Entomologia, vol. 2, fasc. 2, marco 1932</pageTitle>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">
<pageTitle>
<pageNumber pageNumber="239">239</pageNumber>
</pageTitle>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">
that your 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">pickeli</taxonomicName>
is distinct. Apart from the difference in the shape of the head, your species differs in the somewhat smaller mandibular teeth, more oblique mandibular border, more distinct metanotal sclerite (especially mesometanotal suture), anteroposteriorly thicker petiolar node, shorter and more appressed pubescence on the body and legs and less abundant pilosity on the head and thorax. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.bestMatchDistance="279" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">A. pickeli</taxonomicName>
is, also close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24993" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga wheeleri Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">A. wheeleri Mann</taxonomicName>
from Honduras, but is much less hairy. I am sending by return mail some specimens of an 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2324" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acropyga</taxonomicName>
from Para, Brazil, collected by William Beebe, which are still different, having a much more elongated head. They seem to represent a 
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
and I should be glad if you would describe it in connection with your work on Brazilian ants.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">
«Now, in regard to the question of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">pickeli</taxonomicName>
being ithe same as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24941" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga decedens (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decedens">decedens Mayr</taxonomicName>
, I am not able to help you with a comparison of your specimens with typical material, because I have never seen this species, but Mayr's description and Emery's figure, especially the latter, leave not the slightest doubt in my mind that 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24941" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga decedens (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decedens">decedens</taxonomicName>
is a very distinct form. The shape of the head and mandibles are quite different from those of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24951" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga goeldii Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goeldii">goeldii</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">pickeli</taxonomicName>
. I do not see how Costa Lima, who has reproduced Emery's figure side by side with numerous figures of the head of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">pickeli</taxonomicName>
could have reached such an erroneous conclusion...
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">«With kindest greetings and best wishes for the coming year, I remain, cordially yours W. M. Wheeler.»</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">
Segundo ja notei em artigos anteriores, a especie por mim descripta foi comparada por Menozzi com a colleccao de Emery (Museu Civico de Genova), na qual se acham todas as especies de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2324" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acropyga</taxonomicName>
, inclusive cotypos' de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24941" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga decedens (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decedens">A. decedens Mayr</taxonomicName>
. Penso portanto que 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24980" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga pickeli Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pickeli">pickeli</taxonomicName>
deve ser considerada como especie valida, e distincta de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24951" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga goeldii Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goeldii">goeldii For</taxonomicName>
. e 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24941" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acropyga" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acropyga decedens (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decedens">decedens Mayr</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="239">T. Borgmeier</paragraph>
